# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: backstage-idp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:backstage-idp/application-lifecycle-management] ALM is a broader perspective than the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC), which is limited to the phases of software development such as requirements, design, coding, testing, configuration, project management, and change management.
[src:backstage-idp/application-lifecycle-management] ALM continues after development until the application is no longer used, and may span many SDLCs.
[src:backstage-idp/application-lifecycle-management] A research director with research firm Gartner proposed changing the term ALM to ADLM (Application Development Life-cycle Management) to include DevOps, the software engineering culture and practice that aims at unifying software development (Dev) and software operation (Ops).
[src:backstage-idp/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:backstage-idp/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:backstage-idp/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:backstage-idp/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:backstage-idp/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] As such, efforts to define, classify types, or structure metadata are expressed as examples in the context of its use.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" has a history dating to the 1960s where it occurred in computer science and in popular culture.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Different types of metadata serve different functions.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example, descriptive metadata for a document might include the author, creation date, file size and keywords.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] It can help users find relevant information and discover resources.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] It can also help organize electronic resources, provide digital identification, and archive and preserve resources.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata allows users to access resources by "allowing resources to be found by relevant criteria, identifying resources, bringing similar resources together, distinguishing dissimilar resources, and giving location information".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata of telecommunication activities including Internet traffic is very widely collected by various national governmental organizations.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This data is used for the purposes of traffic analysis and can be used for mass surveillance.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Unique metadata standards exist for different disciplines (e.g., museum collections, digital audio files, websites, etc.).
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Describing the contents and context of data or data files increases its usefulness.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example, a web page may include metadata specifying what software language the page is written in (e.g., HTML), what tools were used to create it, what subjects the page is about, and where to find more information about the subject.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This metadata can automatically improve the reader's experience and make it easier for users to find the web page online.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] A CD may include metadata providing information about the musicians, singers, and songwriters whose work appears on the disc.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] In many countries, government organizations routinely store metadata about emails, telephone calls, web pages, video traffic, IP connections, and cell phone locations.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata is not strictly bound to one of these categories, as it can describe a piece of data in many other ways.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] While the metadata application is manifold, covering a large variety of fields, there are specialized and well-accepted models to specify types of metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Bretherton & Singley (1994) distinguish between two distinct classes: structural/control metadata and guide metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes the structure of database objects such as tables, columns, keys and indexes.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] *Guide metadata* helps humans find specific items and is usually expressed as a set of keywords in a natural language.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] According to Ralph Kimball, metadata can be divided into three categories: *technical metadata* (or internal metadata), *business metadata* (or external metadata), and *process metadata*.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Business metadata is important because it can greatly facilitate the usefulness of the data to business people.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] A simple example of business metadata is a glossary entry.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Hover functionality in an application or web form can enable a glossary definition to be shown when cursor is on a field or term.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Other examples of business metadata include annotation ability within applications.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example, a business user may be viewing a business intelligence (BI) report and notice a trend in the data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The user may have background knowledge as to why this trend occurs.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Some business intelligence tools enable the user to create an annotation within the report that explains the trend.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Such an annotation can enhance other users' understanding of the data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This example is especially powerful because it is created by a business user for the use of other business people.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] NISO distinguishes three types of metadata: descriptive, structural, and administrative.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] *Descriptive metadata* is typically used for discovery and identification, as information to search and locate an object, such as title, authors, subjects, keywords, and publisher.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes how the components of an object are organized.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] An example of structural metadata would be how pages are ordered to form chapters of a book.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Finally, *administrative metadata* gives information to help manage the source.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Administrative metadata refers to the technical information, such as file type, or when and how the file was created.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Two sub-types of administrative metadata are rights management metadata and preservation metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] *Rights management metadata* explains intellectual property rights, while *preservation metadata* contains information to preserve and save a resource.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] An additional type of metadata beginning to be more developed is *accessibility metadata*.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Accessibility metadata is not a new concept to libraries; however, advances in universal design have raised its profile.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Projects like Cloud4All and GPII identified the lack of common terminologies and models to describe the needs and preferences of users and information that fits those needs as a major gap in providing universal access solutions.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Those types of information are accessibility metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The Schema.org website has incorporated several accessibility properties based on IMS Global Access for All Information Model Data Element Specification.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] While the efforts to describe and standardize the varied accessibility needs of information seekers are beginning to become more robust, their adoption into established metadata schemas has not been as developed.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example, while Dublin Core (DC)'s "audience" and MARC 21's "reading level" could be used to identify resources suitable for users with dyslexia and DC's "format" could be used to identify resources available in braille, audio, or large print formats, there is more work to be done.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata was traditionally used in the card catalogs of libraries until the 1980s when libraries converted their catalog data to digital databases.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] In the 2000s, as data and information were increasingly stored digitally, this digital data was described using metadata standards.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] An early description of "meta data" for computer systems was written by David Griffel and Stuart McIntosh at the MIT Center for International Studies in 1967: "In summary then, we have statements in an object language about subject descriptions of data and token codes for the data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata is defined as the data providing information about one or more aspects of the data; it is used to summarize basic information about data that can make tracking and working with specific data easier.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example, a digital image may include metadata that describes the size of the image, its color depth, resolution, when it was created, the shutter speed, and other data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] A text document's metadata may contain information about how long the document is, who the author is, when the document was written, and a short summary of the document.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata within web pages can also contain descriptions of page content, as well as key words linked to the content.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] These links are often called "Metatags", which were used as the primary factor in determining order for a web search until the late 1990s.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The reliance on metatags in web searches was decreased in the late 1990s because of "keyword stuffing", whereby metatags were being largely misused to trick search engines into thinking some websites had more relevance in the search than they really did.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata can be stored and managed in a database, often called a metadata registry or metadata repository.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] However, without context and a point of reference, it might be impossible to identify metadata just by looking at it.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example: by itself, a database containing several numbers, all 13 digits long could be the results of calculations or a list of numbers to plug into an equation – without any other context, the numbers themselves can be perceived as the data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] But if given the context that this database is a log of a book collection, those 13-digit numbers may now be identified as ISBNs – information that refers to the book, but is not itself the information within the book.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" was coined in 1968 by Philip Bagley, in his book "Extension of Programming Language Concepts" where it is clear that he uses the term in the ISO 11179 "traditional" sense, which is "structural metadata" i.e.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] "data about the containers of data"; rather than the alternative sense "content about individual instances of data content" or metacontent, the type of data usually found in library catalogs.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Since then the fields of information management, information science, information technology, librarianship, and GIS have widely adopted the term.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] In these fields, the word *metadata* is defined as "data about data".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] While this is the generally accepted definition, various disciplines have adopted their own more specific explanations and uses of the term.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) or, more correctly, the vocabularies used to assemble metadata (metacontent) statements, is typically structured according to a standardized concept using a well-defined metadata scheme, including metadata standards and metadata models.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Tools such as controlled vocabularies, taxonomies, thesauri, data dictionaries, and metadata registries can be used to apply further standardization to the metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Structural metadata commonality is also of paramount importance in data model development and in database design.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) syntax refers to the rules created to structure the fields or elements of metadata (metacontent).
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] A single metadata scheme may be expressed in a number of different markup or programming languages, each of which requires a different syntax.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example, Dublin Core may be expressed in plain text, HTML, XML, and RDF.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] A common example of (guide) metacontent is the bibliographic classification, the subject, the Dewey Decimal class number.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] There is always an implied statement in any "classification" of some object.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] To classify an object as, for example, Dewey class number 514 (Topology) (i.e. books having the number 514 on their spine) the implied statement is: "<book><subject heading><514>".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This is a subject-predicate-object triple, or more importantly, a class-attribute-value triple.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The first 2 elements of the triple (class, attribute) are pieces of some structural metadata having a defined semantic.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The third element is a value, preferably from some controlled vocabulary, some reference (master) data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The combination of the metadata and master data elements results in a statement which is a metacontent statement i.e.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] All of these elements can be thought of as "vocabulary".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Both metadata and master data are vocabularies that can be assembled into metacontent statements.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] There are many sources of these vocabularies, both meta and master data: UML, EDIFACT, XSD, Dewey/UDC/LoC, SKOS, ISO-25964, Pantone, Linnaean Binomial Nomenclature, etc.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The process indexes pages and then matches text strings using its complex algorithm; there is no intelligence or "inferencing" occurring, just the illusion thereof.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can be hierarchical in nature where relationships exist between metadata elements and elements are nested so that parent-child relationships exist between the elements.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] An example of a hierarchical metadata schema is the IEEE LOM schema, in which metadata elements may belong to a parent metadata element.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can also be one-dimensional, or linear, where each element is completely discrete from other elements and classified according to one dimension only.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] An example of a linear metadata schema is the Dublin Core schema, which is one-dimensional.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata are often 2 dimensional, or planar, where each element is completely discrete from other elements but classified according to 2 orthogonal dimensions.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The degree to which the data or metadata is structured is referred to as "granularity".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] "Granularity" refers to how much detail is provided.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata with a high granularity allows for deeper, more detailed, and more structured information and enables a greater level of technical manipulation.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] A lower level of granularity means that metadata can be created for considerably lower costs but will not provide as detailed information.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The major impact of granularity is not only on creation and capture, but moreover on maintenance costs.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] As soon as the metadata structures become outdated, so too is the access to the referred data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Hence granularity must take into account the effort to create the metadata as well as the effort to maintain it.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] In all cases where the metadata schemata exceed the planar depiction, some type of hypermapping is required to enable display and view of metadata according to chosen aspect and to serve special views.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Hypermapping frequently applies to layering of geographical and geological information overlays.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] International standards apply to metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Much work is being accomplished in the national and international standards communities, especially ANSI (American National Standards Institute) and ISO (International Organization for Standardization) to reach a consensus on standardizing metadata and registries.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The core metadata registry standard is ISO/IEC 11179 Metadata Registries (MDR), the framework for the standard is described in ISO/IEC 11179-1:2004.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] A new edition of Part 1 is in its final stage for publication in 2015 or early 2016.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] It has been revised to align with the current edition of Part 3, ISO/IEC 11179-3:2013 which extends the MDR to support the registration of Concept Systems.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This standard specifies a schema for recording both the meaning and technical structure of the data for unambiguous usage by humans and computers.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 standard refers to metadata as information objects about data, or "data about data".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] In ISO/IEC 11179 Part-3, the information objects are data about Data Elements, Value Domains, and other reusable semantic and representational information objects that describe the meaning and technical details of a data item.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This standard also prescribes the details for a metadata registry, and for registering and administering the information objects within a Metadata Registry.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 Part 3 also has provisions for describing compound structures that are derivations of other data elements, for example through calculations, collections of one or more data elements, or other forms of derived data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This standard has become the general basis for other kinds of metadata registries, reusing and extending the registration and administration portion of the standard.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The Geospatial community has a tradition of specialized geospatial metadata standards, particularly building on traditions of map- and image-libraries and catalogs.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Formal metadata is usually essential for geospatial data, as common text-processing approaches are not applicable.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The Dublin Core metadata terms are a set of vocabulary terms that can be used to describe resources for the purposes of discovery.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The W3C Data Catalog Vocabulary (DCAT) is an RDF vocabulary that supplements Dublin Core with classes for Dataset, Data Service, Catalog, and Catalog Record.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] DCAT also uses elements from FOAF, PROV-O, and OWL-Time.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] DCAT provides an RDF model to support the typical structure of a catalog that contains records, each describing a dataset or service.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Although not a standard, Microformat (also mentioned in the section metadata on the internet below) is a web-based approach to semantic markup which seeks to re-use existing HTML/XHTML tags to convey metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Microformat follows XHTML and HTML standards but is not a standard in itself.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] In metadata, Naming and Design Rules are a set of guidelines and naming conventions that go beyond what a single data exchange standard specification will permit.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] The most common standard that Naming and Design Rules are created on is XML Schema.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] For example, the use of upper camel case data element names is a convention used in many standard but is not specified by the XML Schema specification.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Naming and Design Rules have become an important aspect of each organizations data exchange standards.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Within the United States, Naming and Design Rules standards are recommended for each federal and state agency.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Most common types of computer files can embed metadata, including documents, (e.g.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Microsoft Office files, OpenDocument files, PDF) images, (e.g.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata may be added to files by users, but some metadata is often automatically added to files by authoring applications or by devices used to produce the files, without user intervention.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] While metadata in files are useful for finding them, they can be a privacy hazard when the files are shared.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Using metadata removal tools to clean files before sharing them can mitigate this risk.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Some metadata is created by the camera such as, color space, color channels, exposure time, and aperture (EXIF), while some is input by the photographer and/or software after downloading to a computer.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Most digital cameras write metadata about the model number, shutter speed, etc., and some enable you to edit it; this functionality has been available on most Nikon DSLRs since the Nikon D3, on most new Canon cameras since the Canon EOS 7D, and on most Pentax DSLRs since the Pentax K-3.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata can be used to make organizing in post-production easier with the use of key-wording.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Filters can be used to analyze a specific set of photographs and create selections on criteria like rating or capture time.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] On devices with geolocation capabilities like GPS (smartphones in particular), the location the photo was taken from may also be included.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Photographic Metadata Standards are governed by organizations that develop the following standards.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata is particularly useful in video, where information about its contents (such as transcripts of conversations and text descriptions of its scenes) is not directly understandable by a computer, but where an efficient search of the content is desirable.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] This is particularly useful in video applications such as Automatic Number Plate Recognition and Vehicle Recognition Identification software, wherein license plate data is saved and used to create reports and alerts.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Avid's MetaSync and Adobe's Bridge are examples of professional video editing software with access to metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Various file systems are utilising metadata, such as FAT32 and NTFS.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Information on the times, origins and destinations of phone calls, electronic messages, instant messages, and other modes of telecommunication, as opposed to message content, is another form of metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Geospatial metadata relates to Geographic Information Systems (GIS) files, maps, images, and other data that is location-based.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] Metadata is used in GIS to document the characteristics and attributes of geographic data, such as database files and data that is developed within a GIS.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p01] It includes details like who developed the data, when it was collected, how it was processed, and what formats it's available in, and then delivers the context for the data to be used effectively.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata can be created either by automated information processing or by manual work.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Elementary metadata captured by computers can include information about when an object was created, who created it, when it was last updated, file size, and file extension.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] A metadata engine collects, stores and analyzes information about data and metadata in use within a domain.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Data virtualization emerged in the 2000s as the new software technology to complete the virtualization "stack" in the enterprise.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata is used in data virtualization servers which are enterprise infrastructure components, alongside database and application servers.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata in these servers is saved as persistent repository and describe business objects in various enterprise systems and applications.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Structural metadata commonality is also important to support data virtualization.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Standardization and harmonization work has brought advantages to industry efforts to build metadata systems in the statistical community.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Several metadata guidelines and standards such as the European Statistics Code of Practice and ISO 17369:2013 (Statistical Data and Metadata Exchange or SDMX) provide key principles for how businesses, government bodies, and other entities should manage statistical data and metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Entities such as Eurostat, European System of Central Banks, and the U.S.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Environmental Protection Agency have implemented these and other such standards and guidelines with the goal of improving "efficiency when managing statistical business processes".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata has been used in various ways as a means of cataloging items in libraries in both digital and analog formats.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Such data helps classify, aggregate, identify, and locate a particular book, DVD, magazine, or any object a library might hold in its collection.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Until the 1980s, many library catalogs used 3x5 inch cards in file drawers to display a book's title, author, subject matter, and an abbreviated alpha-numeric string (call number) which indicated the physical location of the book within the library's shelves.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The Dewey Decimal System employed by libraries for the classification of library materials by subject is an early example of metadata usage.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The early paper catalog had information regarding whichever item was described on said card: title, author, subject, and a number as to where to find said item.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Beginning in the 1980s and 1990s, many libraries replaced these paper file cards with computer databases.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] These computer databases make it much easier and faster for users to do keyword searches.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Another form of older metadata collection is the use by the US Census Bureau of what is known as the "Long Form".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The Long Form asks questions that are used to create demographic data to find patterns of distribution.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Libraries employ metadata in library catalogues, most commonly as part of an Integrated Library Management System.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata is obtained by cataloging resources such as books, periodicals, DVDs, web pages or digital images.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This data is stored in the integrated library management system, ILMS, using the MARC metadata standard.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The purpose is to direct patrons to the physical or electronic location of items or areas they seek as well as to provide a description of the item/s in question.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] More recent and specialized instances of library metadata include the establishment of digital libraries including e-print repositories and digital image libraries.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] While often based on library principles, the focus on non-librarian use, especially in providing metadata, means they do not follow traditional or common cataloging approaches.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Given the custom nature of included materials, metadata fields are often specially created e.g. taxonomic classification fields, location fields, keywords, or copyright statement.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Standard file information such as file size and format are usually automatically included.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Library operation has for decades been a key topic in efforts toward international standardization.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Standards for metadata in digital libraries include Dublin Core, METS, MODS, DDI, DOI, URN, PREMIS schema, EML, and OAI-PMH.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Leading libraries in the world give hints on their metadata standards strategies.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] A similar concept is the synset, short for *synonym set*, a group of one or more synonyms that share a common meaning in some context.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Synsets are a fundamental concept in computational linguistics and lexical semantics, most notably used in the WordNet lexical database of English.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The concept has been extended to other languages and multilingual projects such as EuroWordNet, BabelNet, and the Global WordNet initiative.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata for scientific publications is often created by journal publishers and citation databases such as PubMed and Web of Science.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The data contained within manuscripts or accompanying them as supplementary material is less often subject to metadata creation, though they may be submitted to e.g. biomedical databases after publication.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The original authors and database curators then become responsible for metadata creation, with the assistance of automated processes.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Comprehensive metadata for all experimental data is the foundation of the FAIR Guiding Principles, or the standards for ensuring research data are findable, accessible, interoperable, and reusable.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Such metadata can then be utilized, complemented, and made accessible in useful ways.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] OpenAlex is a free online index of over 200 million scientific documents that integrates and provides metadata such as sources, citations, author information, scientific fields, and research topics.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Its API and open source website can be used for metascience, scientometrics, and novel tools that query this semantic web of papers.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Another project under development, Scholia, uses the metadata of scientific publications for various visualizations and aggregation features such as providing a simple user interface summarizing literature about a specific feature of the SARS-CoV-2 virus using Wikidata's "main subject" property.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] In research labor, transparent metadata about authors' contributions to works have been proposed – e.g. the role played in the production of the paper, the level of contribution and the responsibilities.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Moreover, various metadata about scientific outputs can be created or complemented – for instance, some organizations attempt to track and link citations of papers as 'Supporting', 'Mentioning' or 'Contrasting' the study.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata in a museum context is the information that trained cultural documentation specialists, such as archivists, librarians, museum registrars and curators, create to index, structure, describe, identify, or otherwise specify works of art, architecture, cultural objects and their images.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Descriptive metadata is most commonly used in museum contexts for object identification and resource recovery purposes.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Many museums and cultural heritage centers recognize that given the diversity of artworks and cultural objects, no single model or standard suffices to describe and catalog cultural works.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] For example, a sculpted Indigenous artifact could be classified as an artwork, an archaeological artifact, or an Indigenous heritage item.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] These standards use HTML and XML markup languages for machine processing, publication and implementation.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The Anglo-American Cataloguing Rules (AACR), originally developed for characterizing books, have also been applied to cultural objects, works of art and architecture.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Standards, such as the CCO, are integrated within a Museum's Collections Management System (CMS), a database through which museums are able to manage their collections, acquisitions, loans and conservation.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Scholars and professionals in the field note that the "quickly evolving landscape of standards and technologies" creates challenges for cultural documentarians, specifically non-technically trained professionals.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Most collecting institutions and museums use a relational database to categorize cultural works and their images.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Relational databases and metadata work to document and describe the complex relationships amongst cultural objects and multi-faceted works of art, as well as between objects and places, people, and artistic movements.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Relational database structures are also beneficial within collecting institutions and museums because they allow for archivists to make a clear distinction between cultural objects and their images; an unclear distinction could lead to confusing and inaccurate searches.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The established institutional cataloging practices, goals, and expertise of cultural documentarians and database structure also influence the information ascribed to cultural objects and the ways in which cultural objects are categorized.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Additionally, museums often employ standardized commercial collection management software that prescribes and limits the ways in which archivists can describe artworks and cultural objects.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] As well, collecting institutions and museums use Controlled Vocabularies to describe cultural objects and artworks in their collections.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Getty Vocabularies and the Library of Congress Controlled Vocabularies are reputable within the museum community and are recommended by CCO standards.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Museums are encouraged to use controlled vocabularies that are contextual and relevant to their collections and enhance the functionality of their digital information systems.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Controlled Vocabularies are beneficial within databases because they provide a high level of consistency, improving resource retrieval.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata structures, including controlled vocabularies, reflect the ontologies of the systems from which they were created.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Often the processes through which cultural objects are described and categorized through metadata in museums do not reflect the perspectives of the maker communities.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata has been instrumental in the creation of digital information systems and archives within museums and has made it easier for museums to publish digital content online.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This has enabled audiences who might not have had access to cultural objects due to geographic or economic barriers to have access to them.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] In the 2000s, as more museums have adopted archival standards and created intricate databases, discussions about Linked Data between museum databases have come up in the museum, archival, and library science communities.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Collection Management Systems (CMS) and Digital Asset Management tools can be local or shared systems.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Digital Humanities scholars note many benefits of interoperability between museum databases and collections, while also acknowledging the difficulties of achieving such interoperability.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Problems involving metadata in litigation in the United States are becoming widespread.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Courts have looked at various questions involving metadata, including the discoverability of metadata by parties.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The Federal Rules of Civil Procedure have specific rules for discovery of electronically stored information, and subsequent case law applying those rules has elucidated on the litigant's duty to produce metadata when litigating in federal court.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] In October 2009, the Arizona Supreme Court has ruled that metadata records are public record.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Document metadata have proven particularly important in legal environments in which litigation has requested metadata, that can include sensitive information detrimental to a certain party in court.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Using metadata removal tools to "clean" or redact documents can mitigate the risks of unwittingly sending sensitive data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This process partially (see data remanence) protects law firms from potentially damaging leaking of sensitive data through electronic discovery.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Opinion polls have shown that 45% of Americans are "not at all confident" in the ability of social media sites to ensure their personal data is secure and 40% say that social media sites should not be able to store any information on individuals.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] 76% of Americans say that they are not confident that the information advertising agencies collect on them is secure and 50% say that online advertising agencies should not be allowed to record any of their information at all.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] In the EU, the Snowden disclosures have been influential in its review of matters concerning privacy and the processing of personal data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] As of 2025, of the 18 European countries surveyed by the Data Retention Directive, only Germany, the Netherlands and Romania do not have any data retention rules in force.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] On 6 October 2020, the Court of Justice for the European Union (CJEU) ruled that indiscriminate mass data retention schemes are illegal under EU law.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] With France passing a law on 18 December 2013 that facilitates the collection of data by the French military and intelligence services.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] While in April 2022 the Portuguese Constitutional Court declared unconstitutional the CJEU laws on the retention of data generated or processed in connection with the provision of publicly available electronic communications services or of public communications networks.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] In Australia, the need to strengthen national security has resulted in the introduction of a new metadata storage law.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This new law means that both security and policing agencies will be allowed to access up to 2 years of an individual's metadata, with the aim of making it easier to stop any terrorist attacks and serious crimes from happening.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Legislative metadata has been discussed in various forums, such as workshops held by the Legal Information Institute at the Cornell Law School on 22 and 23 March 2010.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The documentation for these workshops is titled "Suggested metadata practices for legislation and regulations".
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Australian medical research pioneered the definition of metadata for applications in health care.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] That approach offers the first recognized attempt to adhere to international standards in medical sciences instead of defining a proprietary standard under the World Health Organization (WHO) umbrella.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The medical community yet did not approve of the need to follow metadata standards despite research that supported these standards.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Research studies in the fields of biomedicine and molecular biology frequently yield large quantities of data, including results of genome or meta-genome sequencing, proteomics data, and even notes or plans created during the course of research itself.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Each data type involves its own variety of metadata and the processes necessary to produce these metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] General metadata standards, such as ISA-Tab, allow researchers to create and exchange experimental metadata in consistent formats.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Specific experimental approaches frequently have their own metadata standards and systems: metadata standards for mass spectrometry include mzML and SPLASH, while XML-based standards such as PDBML and SRA XML serve as standards for macromolecular structure and sequencing data, respectively.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The products of biomedical research are generally realized as peer-reviewed manuscripts and these publications are yet another source of data .
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] A data warehouse (DW) is a repository of an organization's electronically stored data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Data warehouses are designed to manage and store the data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Data warehouses differ from business intelligence (BI) systems because BI systems are designed to use data to create reports and analyze the information, to provide strategic guidance to management.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata is an important tool in how data is stored in data warehouses.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The purpose of a data warehouse is to house standardized, structured, consistent, integrated, correct, "cleaned" and timely data, extracted from various operational systems in an organization.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The extracted data are integrated in the data warehouse environment to provide an enterprise-wide perspective.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Data are structured in a way to serve the reporting and analytic requirements.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The design of structural metadata commonality using a data modeling method such as entity-relationship model diagramming is important in any data warehouse development effort.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] They detail metadata on each piece of data in the data warehouse.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] An essential component of a data warehouse/business intelligence system is the metadata and tools to manage and retrieve the metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Ralph Kimball describes metadata as the DNA of the data warehouse as metadata defines the elements of the data warehouse and how they work together.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Kimball et al. refer to three main categories of metadata: technical, business and process.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Technical metadata is primarily definitional, while business metadata and process metadata are primarily descriptive.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The HTML format used to define web pages allows for the inclusion of a variety of types of metadata, from basic descriptive text, dates and keywords to further advanced metadata schemes such as the Dublin Core, e-GMS, and AGLS standards.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Pages and files can also be geotagged with coordinates, categorized or tagged, including collaboratively such as with folksonomies.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] When media has identifiers set or when such can be generated, information such as file tags and descriptions can be pulled or scraped from the Internet – for example about movies.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Various online databases are aggregated and provide metadata for various data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The collaboratively built Wikidata has identifiers not just for media but also abstract concepts, various objects, and other entities, that can be looked up by humans and machines to retrieve useful information and to link knowledge in other knowledge bases and databases.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata may be included in the page's header or in a separate file.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Microformats allow metadata to be added to on-page data in a way that regular web users do not see, but computers, web crawlers and search engines can readily access.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Many search engines are cautious about using metadata in their ranking algorithms because of exploitation of metadata and the practice of search engine optimization, SEO, to improve rankings.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] See the Meta element article for further discussion.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This cautious attitude may be justified as people, according to Doctorow, are not executing care and diligence when creating their own metadata and that metadata is part of a competitive environment where the metadata is used to promote the metadata creators own purposes.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Studies show that search engines respond to web pages with metadata implementations, and Google has an announcement on its site showing the meta tags that its search engine understands.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Enterprise search startup Swiftype recognizes metadata as a relevance signal that webmasters can implement for their website-specific search engine, even releasing their own extension, known as Meta Tags 2.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This metadata can be linked to the video media thanks to the video servers.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Most major broadcast sporting events like FIFA World Cup or the Olympic Games use this metadata to distribute their video content to TV stations through keywords.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] It is often the host broadcaster who is in charge of organizing metadata through its *International Broadcast Centre* and its video servers.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This metadata is recorded with the images and entered by metadata operators (*loggers*) who associate in live metadata available in *metadata grids* through software (such as Multicam(LSM) or IPDirector used during the FIFA World Cup or Olympic Games).
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Ecological and environmental metadata is intended to document the "who, what, when, where, why, and how" of data collection for a particular study.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] This typically means which organization or institution collected the data, what type of data, which date(s) the data was collected, the rationale for the data collection, and the methodology used for the data collection.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata should be generated in a format commonly used by the most relevant science community, such as Darwin Core, Ecological Metadata Language, or Dublin Core.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata editing tools exist to facilitate metadata generation (e.g.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata should describe the provenance of the data (where they originated, as well as any transformations the data underwent) and how to give credit for (cite) the data products.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] When first released in 1982, Compact Discs only contained a Table Of Contents (TOC) with the number of tracks on the disc and their length in samples.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Fourteen years later in 1996, a revision of the CD Red Book standard added CD-Text to carry additional metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Shortly thereafter, it became common for personal computers to retrieve metadata from external sources (e.g.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Digital audio formats such as digital audio files superseded music formats such as cassette tapes and CDs in the 2000s.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Digital audio files could be labeled with more information than could be contained in just the file name.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] That descriptive information is called the **audio tag** or audio metadata in general.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Computer programs specializing in adding or modifying this information are called tag editors.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata can be used to name, describe, catalog, and indicate ownership or copyright for a digital audio file, and its presence makes it much easier to locate a specific audio file within a group, typically through use of a search engine that accesses the metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] As different digital audio formats were developed, attempts were made to standardize a specific location within the digital files where this information could be stored.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] As a result, almost all digital audio formats, including mp3, broadcast wav, and AIFF files, have similar standardized locations that can be populated with metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The metadata for compressed and uncompressed digital music is often encoded in the ID3 tag.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Common editors such as TagLib support MP3, Ogg Vorbis, FLAC, MPC, Speex, WavPack TrueAudio, WAV, AIFF, MP4, and ASF file formats.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] With the availability of cloud applications, which include those to add metadata to content, metadata is increasingly available over the Internet.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored either *internally*, in the same file or structure as the data (this is also called *embedded metadata*), or *externally*, in a separate file or field from the described data.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] A data repository typically stores the metadata *detached* from the data but can be designed to support embedded metadata approaches.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored in either human-readable or binary form.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Storing metadata in a human-readable format such as XML can be useful because users can understand and edit it without specialized tools.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] However, text-based formats are rarely optimized for storage capacity, communication time, or processing speed.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] A binary metadata format enables efficiency in all these respects, but requires special software to convert the binary information into human-readable content.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Each relational database system has its own mechanisms for storing metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] In database terminology, this set of metadata is referred to as the catalog.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the information schema, but not all databases implement it, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] For an example of database-specific metadata access methods, see Oracle metadata.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Programmatic access to metadata is possible using APIs such as JDBC, or SchemaCrawler.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] One of the first satirical examinations of the concept of Metadata as we understand it today is American science fiction author Hal Draper's short story, "MS Fnd in a Lbry" (1961).
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Here, the knowledge of all Mankind is condensed into an object the size of a desk drawer, however, the magnitude of the metadata (e.g. catalog of catalogs of... , as well as indexes and histories) eventually leads to dire yet humorous consequences for the human race.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] The story prefigures the modern consequences of allowing metadata to become more important than the real data it is concerned with, and the risks inherent in that eventuality as a cautionary tale.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Documentation refers to all contextual information that explains and describes a dataset, system, or research process to ensure it is understandable, usable, and reusable.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] It covers broad details such as the study background, data collection methods, file inventories, codebooks, data dictionaries, user guides, and workflow notes.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] In contrast, metadata is a specific and highly structured form of documentation that provides standardized information about the data itself—such as the title, creator, file format, size, access conditions, and how files or sections are organized.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Metadata and documentation are therefore related but distinct concepts in information management.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] Both play crucial roles in data governance, usability, and preservation.
[src:backstage-idp/metadata-p02] While documentation gives the full narrative and instructions surrounding the data, metadata offers concise, structured descriptors that help users and systems identify, locate, manage and preserve the data efficiently.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] A **service catalog** (or **catalogue**), is an organized and curated collection of business and information technology services within an enterprise.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Service catalogs are knowledge management tools which designate subject matter experts (SMEs) who answer questions and requests related to the listed service.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Services in the catalog are usually very repeatable and have controlled inputs, outputs, and procedures.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] A service catalog is a means of centralizing all services that are important to the stakeholders of the enterprises which implement and use it.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Given its digital and virtual implementation, via software, the service catalog acts, at a minimum, as a digital registry and a means for highly distributed enterprises to see, find, invoke, and execute services regardless of where they exist in the world.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] This means that people in one part of the world can find and utilize the same services that people in other parts of the world use, eliminating the need to develop and support local services via a federated implementation model.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Centralizing services also acts as a means of identifying service gaps and redundancies that can then be addressed by the enterprise to improve itself.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Service catalogs are implemented in a manner that facilitate the registration, discovery, request, execution, and tracking of desired services for catalog users.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The more descriptive the service details are, the easier it is for end users of the service catalog to find and invoke the services they desire.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] A service catalog is commonly structured in a manner where its registered services are categorized.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] A large percentage of Categories for services are derived from the areas of an enterprise and the functions it performs, such as Information Technology, Operations, and Fulfillment.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Examples of common service categories include Marketing Services, Product Development Services, Fulfillment Services, and Support Services, which are consumed and performed by most businesses.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The purpose of categorization of services is to facilitate service curation, such as how books may be curated in a library.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The utilization of service catalogs allow enterprises to allocate and track resources, both human and systemic, which are required for successful service delivery, operations, and support.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] This allows enterprises to understand where resources are allocated, whether there are too many or too few resources allocated, and whether or not the resources allocated are adequate for purpose.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] It also allows an understanding of what resources are shared between multiple services versus those that are fully dedicated to a single service.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Benefits of implementing and maintaining a service catalog include allowing an enterprise to track and manage metrics that represent the utilization of services and service-related traits, such as those associated with service supply and demand.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] In addition to the above, a service catalog also helps leadership and management better see and understand correlations of service related work, assets, and resources to the people, organizations, and projects that request them.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] An IT service catalog is a subset of an enterprise service catalog and is defined by ITIL, by the book Service Design, to be an exhaustive list of IT-only services that an organization provides or offers to its employees or customers.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The catalog is the only part of the Service Portfolio that is published to customers and is used to support the sale and/or delivery of IT services.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] A user goes to a website to search for a specific service, such as requesting a new laptop, requesting a change in benefits, or adding a new employee to a department.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The service catalog site groups services by category and allows for searching (especially when hundreds or thousands of services are available).
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The user selects a desired service and sees the description and details.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The user enters any pertinent information (contact information, service-specific questions) and submits the request for service.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The request requires approval, and goes through routing, service-level management, and other processes necessary to fulfill the request.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The user may return to the site later to check on the status of a request, or to view overall metrics on how well the organization is performing the services it provides.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Business Unit Managers determine what services to "publish" to end-users via the service catalog.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Business Unit Managers and Analysts would determine what questions are to be asked of the user, any approvals necessary for a request, and what other systems or processes are needed to fulfill the request.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Once the service is defined and the fulfillment process organized, these people or a more technical employee would build the requisite functionality into the service definition and then publish this to the service catalog.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] The use of a service catalog for cloud computing services is an integral part of deploying services on private and public clouds.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Users wishing to consume cloud services would use a cloud service catalog to view what cloud services are available, their function, and know the technologies used to provide the services.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Users would also see the available different service level options based on latency and reliability.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] With this knowledge, users are able to change the configuration of the technologies used to deliver the services based on cost, performance and technology improvements.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] By seeing and understanding the different services available through the cloud users can better appreciate what is available to them, compared to traditional IT whereby one group of users or business unit may be unaware of the technologies available to another unit.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Accessed by self-service portals, service catalogs contain a list of cloud services from which cloud consumers select for self-provisioning of cloud services.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] This removes the need for users to work through various IT departments in order to provision a cloud service, nor are users required to provide detailed IT specifications.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] They are only required to provide business and organization requirements.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] To make selection easier and to speed service deployment, service definitions are often standardized in cloud service catalogs.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] This presents three benefits: improved capacity planning, particularly if standard components are used; quicker service provisioning; and better buying forecasts which helps to lower costs.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Automation is an aspect of cloud service catalog that has been noted.
[src:backstage-idp/service-catalog] Cloud service catalogs have been described as enabling "cloud on auto-pilot" enabling cloud users to build cloud services based on pre-built templates selected from catalogs.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] The Backstage Software Catalog is a centralized system that keeps track of ownership and metadata for all the software in your ecosystem (services, websites, libraries, data pipelines, etc).
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] The catalog is built around the concept of metadata YAML files stored together with the code, which are then harvested and visualized in Backstage.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Backstage and the Backstage Software Catalog make it easy for one team to manage 10 services — and makes it possible for your company to manage thousands of them.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Makes all the software in your company, and who owns it, discoverable.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] No more orphan software hiding in the dark corners of your software ecosystem.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] The Software Catalog is available to browse at `/catalog`.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] If you've followed Getting Started with Backstage, you should be able to browse the catalog at `http://localhost:3000`.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] The source of truth for the components in your software catalog are metadata YAML files stored in source control (GitHub, GitHub Enterprise, GitLab, ...).
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Repositories can include one or multiple metadata files.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Usually the metadata file is located in the repository root.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] This is not a formal requirement & metadata files can be placed anywhere in the repository.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Backstage expects the full URL to the YAML in your source control.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] It is important to note that any kind of software can be registered in Backstage.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Even if the software is not maintained by your company (SaaS offering, for example) it is still useful to create components for tracking ownership.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] All software created through the Backstage Software Templates are automatically registered in the catalog.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] In addition to manually registering components, it is also possible to register components through static configuration.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] More information about catalog configuration can be found here.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Teams owning the components are responsible for maintaining the metadata about them, and do so using their normal Git workflow.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Once the change has been merged, Backstage will automatically show the updated metadata in the software catalog after a short while.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] By default, the software catalog shows components owned by the team of the logged in user.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] But you can also switch to *All* to see all the components across your company's software ecosystem.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Basic inline *search* and *column filtering* makes it easy to browse a big set of components.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] The software catalog is a great way to organize the infrastructure tools you use to manage the software.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] This is how Backstage creates one developer portal for all your tools.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Rather than asking teams to jump between different infrastructure user interfaces (and incurring additional cognitive overhead each time they make a context switch), most of these tools can be organized around the entities in the catalog.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Your Backstage developer portal can be customized by incorporating existing open source plugins, or by building your own.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] Sometimes entities fail to process correctly.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] The **Unprocessed Entities** feature helps Backstage admins find and diagnose these entities to understand the state of the catalog.
[src:backstage-idp/software-catalog] To use this feature, check out the documentation for the catalog-unprocessed-entities plugin and its backend module.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Documentation is an important part of software engineering.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Requirements documentation is the description of what a given software does or should do.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is used throughout development to communicate how the software functions or how it is intended to operate.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is also used as an agreement or as the foundation for agreement on what the software will do.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Requirements are produced and consumed by everyone involved in the production of software, including: end users, customers, project managers, sales, marketing, software architects, usability engineers, interaction designers, developers, and testers.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Requirements come in a variety of styles, notations and formality.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Requirements can be goal-like (e.g., *distributed work environment*), close to design (e.g., *builds can be started by right-clicking a configuration file and selecting the 'build' function*), and anything in between.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] They can be specified as statements in natural language, as drawn figures, as detailed mathematical formulas, or as a combination of them all.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The variation and complexity of requirement documentation make it a proven challenge.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Requirements may be implicit and hard to uncover.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is difficult to know exactly how much and what kind of documentation is needed and how much can be left to the architecture and design documentation, and it is difficult to know how to document requirements considering the variety of people who shall read and use the documentation.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Thus, requirements documentation is often incomplete (or non-existent).
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Without proper requirements documentation, software changes become more difficult — and therefore more error prone (decreased software quality) and time-consuming (expensive).
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The need for requirements documentation is typically related to the complexity of the product, the impact of the product, and the life expectancy of the software.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] If the software is very complex or developed by many people (e.g., mobile phone software), requirements can help better communicate what to achieve.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] If the software is safety-critical and can have a negative impact on human life (e.g., nuclear power systems, medical equipment, mechanical equipment), more formal requirements documentation is often required.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] If the software is expected to live for only a month or two (e.g., very small mobile phone applications developed specifically for a certain campaign) very little requirements documentation may be needed.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] If the software is a first release that is later built upon, requirements documentation is very helpful when managing the change of the software and verifying that nothing has been broken in the software when it is modified.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Traditionally, requirements are specified in requirements documents (e.g. using word processing applications and spreadsheet applications).
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] To manage the increased complexity and changing nature of requirements documentation (and software documentation in general), database-centric systems and special-purpose requirements management tools are advocated.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] In Agile software development, requirements are often expressed as *user stories* with accompanying acceptance criteria.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] User stories are typically part of a feature, or an epic, which is a broader functionality or set of related functionalities that deliver a specific value to the user based on the business requirements.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Architecture documentation (also known as software architecture description) is a special type of design document.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] In a way, architecture documents are third derivative from the code (design document being second derivative, and code documents being first).
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Very little in the architecture documents is specific to the code.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] These documents do not describe how to program a given routine, or even why a routine exists in the form that it does, but instead merely list the general requirements that would motivate the existence of such a routine.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] A good architecture document is short on details but thick on explanation.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It may suggest approaches for lower level design, but leave the actual exploration trade studies to other documents.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Another type of design document is the comparison document, or trade study.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] This would often take the form of a *whitepaper*.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It focuses on one specific aspect of the system and suggests alternate approaches.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It could be at the user interface, code, design, or even architectural level.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It will outline what the situation is, describe one or more alternatives, and enumerate the pros and cons of each.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] A good trade study document is heavy on research, expresses its idea clearly (without relying heavily on obtuse jargon to dazzle the reader), and most importantly is impartial.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It should honestly and clearly explain the costs of whatever solution it offers as best.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The objective of a trade study is to devise the best solution, rather than to advance some viewpoint.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is acceptable to state no conclusion, or to conclude that none of the alternatives are sufficiently better than the baseline to warrant a change.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It should be approached as a scientific endeavor, not as a marketing technique.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] A very important part of the design document in enterprise software development is the Database Design Document (DDD).
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It contains Conceptual, Logical, and Physical Design Elements.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The DDD includes the formal information that the people who interact with the database need.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The purpose of preparing it is to create a common source to be used by all players within the scene.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is very important to include all information that is to be used by all actors in the scene.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is also very important to update the documents as any change occurs in the database as well.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is important for the code documents associated with the source code (which may include README files and application programming interface (API) documentation) to be thorough, but not so verbose that it becomes overly time-consuming or difficult to maintain them.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Various how-to and overview documentation guides are commonly found specific to the software application or software product being documented by API writers.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] This documentation may be used by developers, testers, and also end-users.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Today, a lot of high-end applications are seen in the fields of power, energy, transportation, networks, aerospace, safety, security, industry automation, and a variety of other domains.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Technical documentation has become important within such organizations as the basic and advanced level of information may change over a period of time with architecture changes.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] There is evidence that the existence of good code documentation actually reduces maintenance costs for software.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Code documents are often organized into a *reference guide* style, allowing a programmer to quickly look up an arbitrary function or class.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The idea of auto-generating documentation is attractive to programmers for various reasons.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] For example, because it is extracted from the source code (for example, through comments), the programmer can write it while referring to the code, and use the same tools used to create the source code to make the documentation.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] This makes it much easier to keep the documentation up-to-date.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] A possible downside is that only programmers can edit this kind of documentation, and it depends on them to refresh the output (for example, by running a cron job to update the documents nightly).
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Some would characterize this as a pro rather than a con.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Respected computer scientist Donald Knuth has noted that documentation can be a very difficult afterthought process and has advocated literate programming (LP), written at the same time and location as the source code and extracted by automatic means.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The programming languages Haskell and CoffeeScript have built-in support for a simple form of LP, but this support is not used widely.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Elucidative programming is the result of practical applications of literate programming in real programming contexts.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The elucidative paradigm proposes that source code and documentation be stored separately.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Often, software developers need to be able to create and access information that is not going to be part of the source file itself.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Such annotations are usually part of several software development activities, such as code walks and porting, where third-party source code is analysed in a functional way.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Annotations can therefore help the developer during any stage of software development where a formal documentation system would hinder progress.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Unlike code documents, user documents simply describe how a program is used.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] In the case of a software library, the code documents and user documents could in some cases be effectively equivalent and worth conjoining, but for a general application this is not often true.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Typically, the user documentation describes each feature of the program, and assists the user in realizing these features.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is very important for user documents to not be confusing, and for them to be up to date.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] User documents do not need to be organized in any given way, but it is very important for them to have a thorough index.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Consistency and simplicity are also very valuable.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] User documentation is considered to constitute a contract specifying what the software will do.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] API Writers are very well accomplished towards writing good user documents as they would be well aware of the software architecture and programming techniques used.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] User documentation can be produced in a variety of online and print formats.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] *Thematic* – A thematic approach, where chapters or sections concentrate on one given area of interest, is of more general use to an intermediate user.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Some authors prefer to convey ideas through a knowledge based article to facilitate the user needs.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] This approach is usually practiced by a dynamic industry, such as Information technology.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] *List or Reference* – The final type of organizing principle is one in which commands or tasks are simply listed alphabetically or logically grouped, often via cross-referenced indexes.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] This latter approach is of greater use to advanced users who know exactly what sort of information they are looking for.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] A common complaint among users regarding software documentation is that only one of these three approaches was taken to the near-exclusion of the other two.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] It is common to limit provided software documentation for personal computers to online help that gives only reference information on commands or menu items.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The job of tutoring new users or helping more experienced users get the most out of a program is left to private publishers, who are often given significant assistance by the software developer.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Like other forms of technical documentation, good user documentation benefits from an organized process of development.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Planning, or the actual documentation phase.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Draft review, is a self-explanatory phase where feedback is sought on the draft composed in the previous step.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Usability testing, whereby the usability of the document is tested empirically.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Editing, is the final step in which the information collected in steps three and four is used to produce the final draft.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] For many applications it is necessary to have some promotional materials to encourage casual observers to spend more time learning about the product.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] To inform them about what exactly the product does, so that their expectations are in line with what they will be receiving.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] To explain the position of this product with respect to other alternatives.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] "The resistance to documentation among developers is well known and needs no emphasis." This situation is common in agile software development because those methodologies try to avoid needless activities that add no direct value.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] The Agile Manifesto advocates valuing "working software over comprehensive documentation", which could be interpreted cynically as "We want to spend all our time coding.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] A survey among software engineering experts revealed, however, that documentation is by no means considered unnecessary in agile development.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Yet it is acknowledged that there are motivational problems in development, and that documentation methods tailored to agile development (e.g. through Reputation systems and Gamification) may be needed.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Combining Docs as Code with Agile methods creates a robust framework for maintaining high-quality, up-to-date documentation.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] *Automate Processes* – Implement CI/CD tools to automate generating and deploying documentation.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] *Define Roles* – Assign roles and responsibilities for documentation within the Agile team.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] Ensure everyone understands the importance of documentation.
[src:backstage-idp/software-documentation] *Regular Reviews* – Schedule regular documentation reviews as part of the sprint retrospectives.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A **web portal** is a specially designed website that brings information from diverse sources, like emails, online forums and search engines, together in a uniform way.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Usually, each information source gets its dedicated area on the page for displaying information (a portlet); often, the user can configure which ones to display.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Variants of portals include mashups and intranet dashboards for executives and managers.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The extent to which content is displayed in a "uniform way" may depend on the intended user and the intended purpose, as well as the diversity of the content.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Very often design emphasis is on a certain "metaphor" for configuring and customizing the presentation of the content (e.g., a dashboard or map) and the chosen implementation framework or code libraries.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] In addition, the role of the user in an organization may determine which content can be added to the portal or deleted from the portal configuration.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A portal may use a search engine's application programming interface (API) to permit users to search intranet content as opposed to extranet content by restricting which domains may be searched.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Apart from this common search engines feature, web portals may offer other services such as e-mail, news, stock quotes, information from databases and even entertainment content.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Portals provide a way for enterprises and organizations to provide a consistent "look and feel" with access control and procedures for multiple applications and databases, which otherwise would have been different web entities at various URLs.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The features available may be restricted by whether access is by an authorized and authenticated user (employee, member) or an anonymous website visitor.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] American web portals included Pathfinder, Excite, Netscape's Net Center, Go, NBC, MSN, Lycos, Voila, Yahoo!, and Google Search.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The term "portal" emerged in the late 1990s to describe a new genre of website.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] After the proliferation of Web browsers in the late-1990s, many companies tried to build or acquire a portal to attempt to obtain a share of an Internet market.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The Web portal gained special attention because it was, for many users, the starting point of their Web browsing if it was set as their home page.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The content and branding of a portal could change as Internet companies merged or were acquired.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Netscape became a part of America Online, the Walt Disney Company launched Go.com.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Portal metaphors are widely used by public library sites for borrowers using a login as users and by university intranets for students and for faculty.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Vertical markets remain for independent software vendors (ISVs) offering management and executive intranet "dashboards" for corporations and government agencies in areas such as governance, risk management, and compliance.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Web portals are sometimes classified as *horizontal* or *vertical*.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A horizontal portal is used as a platform to several companies in the same economic sector or to the same type of manufacturers or distributors.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A vertical portal (also known as a "vortal") is a specialized entry point to a specific market or industry niche, subject area, or interest.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Some vertical portals are known as "vertical information portals" (VIPs).
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] VIPs provide news, editorial content, digital publications, and e-commerce capabilities.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] In contrast to traditional vertical portals, VIPs also provide dynamic multimedia applications including social networking, video posting, and blogging.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A news portal is an online gallery, index and search engine for news published online.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] It may cater to specific interest or language or target a wider market.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] For example, in India, the news portal named NS NOW, especially Uttar Pradesh, serves the news online on its website.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A personal portal is a Web Page at a Website on the World Wide Web or a local HTML home page including JavaScript and perhaps running in a modified Web browser.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A personal portal typically provides personalized capabilities to its visitors or its local user, providing a pathway to other content.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] It may be designed to use distributed applications, different numbers and types of middleware and hardware to provide services from a number of different sources and may run on a non-standard local Web server.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] In addition, business portals can be designed for sharing and collaboration in workplaces.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A further business-driven requirement of portals is that the content be presented on multiple platforms such as personal computers, laptops, tablet computers, personal digital assistants (PDAs), cell phones and smartphones.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Information, news, and updates are examples of content that could be delivered through such a portal.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Personal portals can be related to any specific topic such as providing friends information on a social network or providing links to outside content that may help others beyond the reach of services.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Portals are not limited to simply providing links.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Outside of business intranet user, very often simpler portals become replaced with richer mashup designs.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Within enterprises, early portals were often replaced by much more powerful "dashboard" designs.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Some also have relied on newer protocols such as some version of RSS aggregation and may or may not involve some degree of Web harvesting.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] At the end of the dot-com boom in the 1990s, many governments had already committed to creating government web portal sites for their citizens.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] These included primary portals to the governments as well as portals developed for specific branches (e.g., a particular government ministry, department or agency), or for specific sub-audiences (e.g., senior citizens, parents, post-secondary students, etc.).
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Cultural portals aggregate digitised cultural collections of galleries, libraries (see: library portal), archives and museums.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] This type of portal provides a point of access to invisible Web cultural content that may not be indexed by standard search engines.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] These portals are often based around a specific national or regional groupings of institutions.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Corporate intranets became common during the 1990s.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] As intranets grew in size and complexity, organization webmasters were faced with increasing content and user management challenges.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A consolidated view of company information was judged insufficient; users wanted personalization and customization.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Webmasters, if skilled enough, were able to offer some capabilities, but for the most part ended up driving users away from using the intranet.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Many companies began to offer tools to help webmasters manage their data, applications and information more easily, and by providing different users with personalized views.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Portal solutions can also include workflow management, collaboration between work groups or branches, and policy-managed content publication.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Most can allow internal and external access to specific corporate information using secure authentication or single sign-on.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Java Specification Request (JSR) 168 standards allow the interoperability of portlets across different portal platforms.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] These standards allow portal developers, administrators and consumers to integrate standards-based portals and portlets across a variety of vendor solutions.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The concept of content aggregation seems to still gain momentum and portal solution will likely continue to evolve significantly over the next few years.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The Gartner Group predicts generation 8 portals to expand on the Business Mashups concept of delivering a variety of information, tools, applications and access points through a single mechanism.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] With the increase in user-generated content (blog posts, comments, photos), disparate data silos, and file formats, information architects and taxonomists will be required to allow users the ability to tag (classify) the data or content.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] For example, if a vice-president makes a blog post, this post could be tagged with their name, title, and the subject of the post.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Tagging makes it easier for users of the intranet to find the content they are interested in.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] This will ultimately cause a ripple effect where users will also be generating ad hoc navigation and information flows.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Corporate portals also offer customers and employees self-service opportunities.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Search portals aggregate results from several search engines into one page.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Users can find search portals specialized in a product, for example property search portals.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Library search portals are also known as discovery interfaces.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Property search portals aggregate data about properties for sale or rent by real estate agents or vendors.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Notable agent search portals in the UK include Nestoria, Nuroa, OnTheMarket, Rightmove and Zoopla.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Notable vendor (seller or landlord) portals in the UK include OpenRent and Gumtree.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] A tender portal is a gateway for government suppliers to bid on providing goods and services.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Tender portals allow users to search, modify, submit, review and archive data in order to provide a complete online tendering process.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Hosted Web portals gained popularity and a number of companies began offering them as a hosted service.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The hosted portal market fundamentally changed the composition of portals.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] In many ways they served simply as a tool for publishing information instead of the loftier goals of integrating legacy applications or presenting correlated data from distributed databases.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The early hosted portal companies such as Hyperoffice.com or the now defunct InternetPortal.com focused on collaboration and scheduling in addition to the distribution of corporate data.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] As hosted Web portals have risen in popularity their feature set has grown to include hosted databases, document management, email, discussion fora and more.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Hosted portals automatically personalize the content generated from their modules to provide a personalized experience to their users.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] In this regard they have remained true to the original goals of the earlier corporate Web portals.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Cloud portals like Nubifer Cloud Portal show what is possible using Enterprise Mashup and Web Service integration approaches to building cloud portals.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] Along the same lines, industry-specific news and information portals have appeared, such as the clinical trials-specific portal.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The main concept is to present the user with a single Web page that brings together or aggregates content from a number of other systems or servers.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The application server or architecture performs most of the crucial functions of the application.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] This application server is in turn connected to database servers, and may be part of a clustered server environment.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] High-capacity portal configurations may include load balancing strategies.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] For portals that present application functionality to the user, the portal server is in reality the front piece of a server configuration that includes some connectivity to the application server.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] For early Web browsers permitting HTML frameset and iframe elements, diverse information could be presented without violating the browser same-source security policy (relied upon to prevent a variety of cross-site security breaches).
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] More recent client-side technologies rely on JavaScript frameworks and libraries that rely on more recent Web functionality such as WebSockets and asynchronous callbacks using XMLHttpRequests.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] The server hosting the portal may only be a "pass through" for the user.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] By use of portlets, application functionality can be presented in any number of portal pages.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] For the most part, this architecture is transparent to the user.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] In such a design, security and concurrent user capacity can be important issues, and security designers need to ensure that only authenticated and authorized users can generate requests to the application server.
[src:backstage-idp/web-portal] If the security design and administration does not ensure adequate authentication and authorization, then the portal may inadvertently present vulnerabilities to various types of attacks.
[src:backstage-idp/what-is-backstage] Backstage is an open source framework for building developer portals.
[src:backstage-idp/what-is-backstage] Powered by a centralized software catalog, Backstage restores order to your microservices and infrastructure and enables your product teams to ship high-quality code quickly — without compromising autonomy.
[src:backstage-idp/what-is-backstage] Backstage unifies all your infrastructure tooling, services, and documentation to create a streamlined development environment from end to end.
[src:backstage-idp/what-is-backstage] Backstage is a CNCF Incubation project after graduating from Sandbox.
[src:backstage-idp/what-is-backstage] If you have questions or want support, please join our Discord chatroom.
